Eatonville, the first complete black town that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "city of five lakes, three croquet courses, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough quay, two schools and no prison."
Now it's a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Festival Zora! to compliment the Hurstons, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains aside, although she made a stop for tourists by including it in the florid tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project from the time of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what's missing."
Even today, when the Black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on races, many of the people here remain cautious about the views of strangers.
"We pay great attention to how our story is being told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as the paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both the historical model of the Black Rise and the community of almost 2,400 people, where poverty is twice as high as the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also a shadowed example of Southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - which originated from American slavery.
It is not too surprising that the people here are both proud and protective.
And the concerns about the image of Eatonville really began with Zorah, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through a hearty book full of murmurs like "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
The five paragraphs of the florid tourist guide changed the city to road No. 17, which leads through the often blurred center of Florida, into the stage of Black history and human drama.
With the destruction of a large drum in life and in literature, Hurston brought his readers to the store of the first eatonville mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"Left by the road," she wrote, "is a white brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courts and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write."
She also mentioned the new widow's husband Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all sorts and anything that fits into the hourly hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville was connected with self-government, but also with illiteracy, rejuvenating marriages and sex.
This obviously wasn't the typical editor's office of Fodor's.
In fact, it wasn't a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Morning said it as it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
