Héma-Quebec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the founding yesterday, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced because Hema-Quebec became one of the most reliable and inefficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after the scandal of converging blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is commonly known, the state blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Committee was contaminated in the 1980s by the immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and the wave of violence, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, which was chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and making recommendations not to repeat such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying the release of the report, some provinces put in motion a committee designed to plan a new system of blood management in Canada.
In Québek, the Geline Committee took this role.
After Gélineau and Krevere's report, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Héma-Quebec, who was to hold Québec, and Canada's blood company to supply all provinces and territories.
"When Hema-Québec began his activities in 1998, 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system," Décary recalls.
"The situation was depressing.
With a consistent effort to increase the safety of blood products and work in this area, we have regained public confidence over the following years," he says and proudly adds that at the beginning of 2008, Héma-Quebeku trusted almost 94% of the Québé population.
Dr. Decary, however, does not lose sight that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has applied the principle of prudence.
"When we were in Europe, we witnessed the occurrence of many cases of a disease of mad cows, new variants of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says a woman who has been leading society since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea that this disease could spread in blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the main recommendations of Krevere and Gélineau, which, if we do not know and when a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jacob's disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, must be taken with exception.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who had abstained in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that to follow the principle of prudence made sense."
In 1999 a much more accurate technique appeared on the market to detect the HIV virus: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in donor blood, and not the presence of antibodies on which tests were used before.
NAT tests have reduced the deafening period between the patient’s infection and the moment our blood techniques can detect the first viruses, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing about it and without even realizing it.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
One of the 12 million people is exposed today to the risk of receiving HIV - related blood.
"In other words, before someone infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of transmission of HIV through the blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can get the blood transfusions needed to heal in complete peace," says Head of Head Hém-Quebek.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of fetal element in the system can appear.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by stabbing the insect.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," Dr. Décary continues, stressing that, in addition to safe supply, Hema-Quebec must also count on sufficient supplies.
"The needs are growing because the population is ageing.
Because of the more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The population's ageing also has implications for the blood donation network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecians admitted to donation."
Every healthy person at least 18 years of age, corresponding to the eligibility criteria, but he can donate blood only once in 56 days, that means six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not accepted on average because, for example, they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where poor winters are kept, they are excluded for one year.
"With these 3% we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
Members of the donor network, however, need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
But to convince people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life today is so inconceivable that we will rarely find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary will fast.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec not only delivers blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hem-Quebek, which also manages the only public blood bank from the umbilical cord in Québek.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedicine waste, has blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousands of blood samples from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we assume that we will collect over a thousand a year.
At the beginning of next year we should start offering them for transplants," explains Dr. Decary, who describes the blood collection program from the umbilical cord as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they have no access to him," because Hema-Quebec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Québec.
