Coffin Psychology: Why spend more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this famous - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers from the field of neurology and economics of New York University.
According to their study, published in Science, people in the eBay auction competition do not want to hold back, so they would rather pay too much price.
Research by experimental auction attempted to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers waged, the other group took part in a playful auction, with a functional magnetic resonance method (fMRI) examined the active area of the brain of experimental persons.
In both games, participants could win the money, but during the auction, the important element of which is to rewind the other side, began to function intensively under the brain crust, called the striatum.
In addition to many other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "self-refunding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the investigators, it is possible to explain the effort to avoid a sharp reaction of the striath.
To support their theory, members of the research team carried out a financial cross-sectional investigation from a series of economists.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made the bets.
In addition, the members of the other group were promised that if they come out of the game victoriously, they will receive another $15 reward.
On the contrary, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost that money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, all in all, that one was stressed by the win and the other loss.
However, members of the group playing "against the loss" were willing to go higher than they were in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
For you have yet to explain the phenomena that are observable at auctions with joy of victory and avoiding the risk.
Until neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the gap between these two theories so that we have now reached the third explanation," stated Andrew Schotter, professor of the New York University Faculty of Economics.
Hepatitis: when can you find a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and this chronic liver disease is reported among the main causes of death in Hungary.
The number of home cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only 7,000 are being treated, and the reason is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name of the hepatitis is a summary of the names of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, there is a sign of inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the originator of the disease and the disease caused by them differs from one another.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways, depending on the origins of the disease: hepatitis A and E by digestive systems (such as infected foods, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses of blood and body fluids (sperm, animal secretion, saliva).
Travellers should, in any case, protect themselves by vaccination against virus A and B, against the virus type C vaccine does not exist.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected food, usually associated with nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, nausea and vomiting.
After that, yellow, lighty stool and darkening urine will be formed on the skin and eye whites. The treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, millions of people worldwide will die of a more serious type of this disease, liver cancer, and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected medicamentalis is treated.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to hepatic cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people who are infected with their disease do not even know, the disease's cause destroys the liver cells in the background, so the first symptoms will occur in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, regular mapping is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who had blood transfusions before 1991, between drug users and tattoo people.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C is 200 million.
Since the disease can demonstrate a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his or her practical physician if he or she detects any symptoms of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infectious diseases and preventing the formation of cancer.
September 30 is a world day of hepatitis, which was organised for the first time worldwide by organizations representing sick people.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of the virus, and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
