The intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would perhaps be the best method of developing technologies to prevent precipitation, if not imitation detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
A bee, for example.
The starting strategic idea of a surprising project presented at the Japan CEATEC fair was inspired by engineers from Nissan bumbleca. It was about how to build a new generation of precipitation-prohibition systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has constructed a biomimetic robotic control system of type BR23C, a robotic miniauta, which is equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate all precipitation.
"On the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is in fact very much like our security package," explained Kazuhiro Doi, Director-General of the brand for the field of technological PR and research and development.
An important role is played by folded eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions in the visual angle more than 300 degrees.
Engineers were involved in copying the function of a composite eye after the idea of a laser long-range meter.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 metres before BR23C in a visual field of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor that immediately turns into an operation to prevent precipitation.
The obstacle is caught during a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to imitate the movements of the bees and the rotation of the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision from changing immediately.
Unlike any existing system, this dynamic manoeuvre is carried out in an entirely instinctive way.
"If it hadn't been for that, a robot car could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and the most internal layer of the safety package within which the impact is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards, or in an angle, it can only be two-dimensional and only in a direction that can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees while avoiding, only speeding, acceleration and slowing has been applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer accumulators that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, the important instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, is thus less data storage.
This mechanism must process and react to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to store them and react using intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers data, so he is constantly using only a memory of a few kilobytes.
He doesn't need a giga or megabyte capacity memory.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for immediate avoidance, which is estimated to reach a series of manufactured vehicles within ten years.
Another option of application may be to connect a unit to a satellite GPS navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles, would lead the motorist to a given ultimate goal.
